04852nam a22007575i 9780271081540DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212018pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710815407 a10.1515/97802710815402doi  a(DE-B1597)583873  a(OCoLC)1269268689  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aN6554 7aART0440002bisacsh04a709.72/090342231 aMoriuchi, Mey-Yen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMexican Costumbrismo :bRace, Society, and Identity in Nineteenth-Century Art /cMey-Yen Moriuchi. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (180 p.) :b31 color/29 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tchapter 1 Racialized Social Spaces in Casta and Costumbrista Painting -- tchapter 2 Traveler-Artists' Visions of Mexico -- tchapter 3 Literary Costumbrismo: Celebration and Satire of los tipos populares -- tchapter 4 Local Perspectives: Mexican Costumbrista Artists -- tchapter 5 Costumbrista Photography -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe years following Mexican independence in 1821 were critical to the development of social, racial, and national identities. The visual arts played a decisive role in this process of self-definition. Mexican Costumbrismo reorients current understanding of this key period in the history of Mexican art by focusing on a distinctive genre of painting that emerged between 1821 and 1890: costumbrismo.In contrast to the neoclassical work favored by the Mexican academy, costumbrista artists portrayed the "idian lives of the lower to middle classes, their clothes, food, dwellings, and occupations. Based on observations of similitude and difference, costumbrista imagery constructed stereotypes of behavioral and biological traits associated with distinct racial and social classes. In doing so, Mey-Yen Moriuchi argues, these works engaged with notions of universality and difference, contributed to the documentation and reification of social and racial types, and transformed the way Mexicans saw themselves, as well as how other nations saw them, during a time of rapid change for all aspects of national identity.Carefully researched and featuring more than thirty full-color exemplary reproductions of period work, Moriuchi's study is a provocative art-historical examination of costumbrismo's lasting impact on Mexican identity and history.E-book editions have been made possible through support of the Art History Publication Initiative (AHPI), a collaborative grant from the Andrew W. Mellon Foundation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArt, Mexicany19th century. 0aMexican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMexicans in artxHistoryy19th century. 0aMexicans in literaturexHistoryy19th century. 0aNational characteristics, Mexican, in artxHistoryy19th century. 0aNational characteristics, Mexican, in literaturexHistoryy19th century. 7aART / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311074522140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271081540zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271081540423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271081540/original  a978-3-11-074522-1  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_